 {"id":"bd-3dy","title":"Async Phase 2: background metric computation for large graphs","description":"WHAT: For graphs above a configurable size threshold, compute expensive metrics (betweenness centrality, eigenvector centrality) in a background thread while returning fast metrics (PageRank, k-core, degree) immediately. WHY: Go handles this via goroutines in pkg/analysis/analysis.go — expensive metrics compute in background while the TUI shows partial results. Our Rust engine blocks on all metrics before returning anything, which makes large graphs feel sluggish. This is lower priority because most real-world beads graphs are small (<1000 nodes), but it's important for the 'wow factor' on large repos. IMPLEMENTATION: Use std::thread::spawn (not async — we don't have a runtime and don't need one for CPU-bound work). GraphAnalyzer returns AnalysisResult with Option<T> for expensive metrics. TUI polls for completion and re-renders when background metrics arrive. Config system (bd-6gv) provides the size threshold. ACCEPTANCE: Fast metrics return in <100ms regardless of graph size. Expensive metrics fill in within seconds. TUI shows progress indicator while background computation runs. No unsafe code. DEPENDS ON: bd-6gv (config system for thresholds). PARENT: bd-3in","status":"open","priority":3,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:03:26.474517253Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:48.700574507Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-3dy","depends_on_id":"bd-6gv","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:03:44.663067770Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":45,"issue_id":"bd-3dy","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"DESIGN: Two-phase result: AnalysisResult{fast: FastMetrics, slow: Option<SlowMetrics>}. FastMetrics: PageRank, degree, k-core (all O(V+E) or near). SlowMetrics: betweenness (O(VE)), eigenvector (iterative). TUI renders fast immediately, shows spinner for slow, re-renders on completion via channel notification. Thread join on app exit to prevent resource leak.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:09:24Z"},{"id":98,"issue_id":"bd-3dy","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"TESTING REQUIREMENT: This task is NOT complete until it includes inline unit tests. Config: test load/merge/default. Cache: test hit/miss/TTL/invalidation. Feedback: test round-trip/apply/corrupt-file. Async: test fast-return/eventual-complete.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:48Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-3in","title":"Epic 5: Analysis Infrastructure — config, cache, feedback, async","description":"Meta-epic for analysis engine infrastructure: per-metric configuration system, computation cache layer, persistent feedback/scoring adjustments, and async background computation. These are foundational capabilities that multiple robot outputs and TUI features depend on.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"epic","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:02:26.976004868Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-08T00:36:07.661202572Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-3in","depends_on_id":"bd-3dy","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:36:07.190177942Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-3in","depends_on_id":"bd-3qa","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:36:07.660546725Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-3in","depends_on_id":"bd-3ud","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:36:06.753592852Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-3in","depends_on_id":"bd-4h6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:36:06.248096991Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-3in","depends_on_id":"bd-6gv","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:36:05.804251998Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":41,"issue_id":"bd-3in","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"CONTEXT: Foundational infrastructure that multiple features depend on. The config system (bd-6gv) is needed by robot output (bd-1ru.3) and async computation (bd-3dy). The cache (bd-4h6) is needed by WhatIf (bd-ybj.4) for fast delta computation. The feedback loop (bd-3ud) is needed by triage output (bd-1ru.9). ORDER: bd-6gv (config) first since bd-3dy and bd-1ru.3 depend on it. bd-4h6 (cache) is independent. bd-3ud depends on bd-ybj.2 (triage scoring). bd-3dy depends on bd-6gv.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:09:10Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-3m5","title":"Robot output unit tests + e2e validation scripts","description":"WHAT: Comprehensive test coverage for all robot output changes in this epic. THREE layers: (1) Unit tests for each new field/struct — verify serialization shape, field presence, correct types, default values. (2) Conformance tests comparing Rust JSON output against Go reference fixtures for every robot mode (--robot-triage, --robot-plan, --robot-insights, --robot-next, --robot-priority). (3) E2e bash script (scripts/test_robot_output_parity.sh) that runs both bv and bvr against a shared test fixture, diffs the JSON schemas field-by-field, and logs discrepancies with context. LOGGING: Each test should print what it's checking, expected vs actual, and on failure dump the full JSON for debugging. E2e script should use set -euo pipefail, trap for cleanup, and produce a summary report at the end. ACCEPTANCE: All robot outputs have matching JSON schemas. Zero field-name or type mismatches. E2e script passes with exit 0. Conformance fixtures updated. PARENT: bd-1ru","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:25:36.467310033Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-08T00:28:11.780541973Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-3m5","depends_on_id":"bd-1ru.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:27:11.094387354Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-3m5","depends_on_id":"bd-1ru.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:27:11.635123738Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-3m5","depends_on_id":"bd-1ru.3","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:27:11.951541878Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-3m5","depends_on_id":"bd-1ru.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:27:12.461815380Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-3m5","depends_on_id":"bd-1ru.5","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:27:12.870861176Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-3m5","depends_on_id":"bd-1ru.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:27:13.326629454Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-3m5","depends_on_id":"bd-1ru.7","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:27:16.150207549Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-3m5","depends_on_id":"bd-1ru.8","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:27:16.800121142Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-3m5","depends_on_id":"bd-1ru.9","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:27:17.310702881Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":46,"issue_id":"bd-3m5","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"TESTING STRATEGY: This bead covers ALL test artifacts for Epic 1 (Robot Output). Tests should be written incrementally — add unit tests for each field as it's implemented, then the conformance fixtures once all fields exist, then the e2e script as the capstone. The e2e script should be runnable standalone (scripts/test_robot_output_parity.sh) and also integrated into CI. Key insight: Go may not have ALL the fields we're adding (some may be aspirational) — the conformance tests should compare against Go where Go has the field, and validate presence/type where it doesn't. Use insta snapshot tests for JSON shape validation.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:28:11Z"}]}
